<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-668-992  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 668 992.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  Sept 18 1989 n266 p32(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Can today's hacker laws work?andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Watson, Neil.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The indictment of Robert T. Morris, a former Cornell student, forcrippling thousands of computers on the Internet research networkraises the question of the adequacy of current federalcomputer-crime laws.andP;  It also raises data security issues thatshould be addressed.andP;  The key legal issue is one involving ahacker's intent to damage a computer network.andP;  If such intent isproven, the hacker is liable to five years in prison and a$250,000 fine.andP;  Prosecution under this law is expected to increasein the next decade.andP;  Estimates are that computer crime costs USbusinesses and government agencies about $555 million a year,though some estimates of unreported computer crime run to $5billion annually.andP;  The MIS professional can usually outwit thehacker through the employment of common sense authorization andsecurity measures.andP;  In the future, network security tools shouldbe developed to make the hacker's task harder.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer CrimesComputer HackersLegal IssuesSecurity.andO;Person:    Morris, Robert T., Jr. (cases).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>